Appendix AN — Anisotropic Fracture of SCARLET Black Holes in Void Environments (EFT Extension)

(Coupled to Appendix R — Mechanical Fracture, Appendix AM — Coherence Field Dynamics, Appendix W — Torsional Dissipation, Appendix AJ — Spectral Constraints, Appendix AI — Tetrad/Torsion EFT)


AN.1 Overview

In non-uniform cosmological environments, the coherence field \Phi_P(x,t) varies across macroscopic scales. When a SCARLET black hole is embedded in a void–filament system, this spatial variation breaks spherical symmetry.

This appendix generalizes the fracture condition of Appendix R to a direction-dependent (anisotropic) form, producing environment-coupled black hole structure and evolution.


AN.2 External Coherence Field Decomposition

We decompose the coherence field near the black hole as:

\Phi_P(r,\theta,\phi) = \Phi_0(r) + \delta \Phi_{\text{ext}}(\theta,\phi)

Where:

\Phi_0(r): spherically symmetric core contribution (local sourcing; Appendix AM)
\delta \Phi_{\text{ext}}(\theta,\phi): large-scale environmental field (void–filament structure)
Assumption:
|\delta \Phi_{\text{ext}}| \ll \Phi_0 \quad \text{near the core, but dominates asymptotically}


AN.3 Direction-Dependent Fracture Condition

The isotropic condition (Appendix R):

\sigma(r_f) = \sigma_f

is generalized to:

\sigma\big(r_f(\theta,\phi)\big) = \sigma_f\!\left(\Phi_P(\theta,\phi)\right)


AN.4 Coherence-Dependent Failure Threshold

We define:

\sigma_f(\Phi_P) = \sigma_0 \left(1 + \lambda\,\Phi_P\right)

Where:

\sigma_0: intrinsic lattice fracture stress
\lambda: coherence–stiffening coefficient
Properties:

\Phi_P \uparrow \Rightarrow \sigma_f \uparrow (stronger fabric)
\Phi_P \downarrow \Rightarrow \sigma_f \downarrow (weaker fabric)

AN.5 Angular Dependence of the Fracture Radius

Define:

r_f(\theta,\phi) = r_0 + \delta r(\theta,\phi)

with r_0 the isotropic solution.

Linearizing:

\delta r(\theta,\phi) \propto -\lambda\,\delta \Phi_{\text{ext}}(\theta,\phi)


Interpretation

Void-facing direction (low \Phi_P)
→ reduced \sigma_f
→ earlier failure
→ larger r_f
Filament-facing direction (high \Phi_P)
→ increased \sigma_f
→ deeper compression
→ smaller r_f

